               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18391216-name-316" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18391216-name-316" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391216-name-316" type="surname" value="MILLS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391216-name-316" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD MILLS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopman to Mr. Richard Exley, a grocer in Onslow-place, Fulbam-road. On the 14th of December, between one and two o'clock, we had eight cakes of soap outside the shop window—I did not see any body outside—I missed the soap—I went out, and took John<lb></lb>son with it on him—Brown was with him, but he had not got any—they were together after the soap was taken.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18391216-name-317" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18391216-name-317" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391216-name-317" type="surname" value="ANDREWS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391216-name-317" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD ANDREWS</persName>
                  </hi>. 1 live in Pound-terrace, Chelsea. I saw the two prisoners walking up and down opposite the prosecutor's shop—they went and looked at the plums in the window—Jackson then untied his apron, put it over the soap, and took it—Brown was at the corner on the watch—Johnson went on a little way, and Brown went after him.</p>
